\date{2026-05-27}
\title{Morphisms of polynomial endofunctors on types}
\author{fredrikbakke}
\import{stt-macros}
\taxon{Module}

\agda{
module Wild.MorphismsPolynomialEndofunctors where

open import Wild.PolynomialEndofunctors

open import Foundations.Universes
open import Foundations.Sigma
open import Foundations.Functions
open import Foundations.TypeFamilies
}

\subtree[stt-00T8]{
\title{Morphisms of polynomial endofunctors}
\taxon{Definition}
\author{fredrikbakke}

\p{
Given two polynomial endofunctors #{P \coloneqq (A \mathbin{◃} B)} and
#{Q \coloneqq (C \mathbin{◃} D)}, then a \em{morphism} from #{P} to #{Q} is a map
#{f : A \to C} together with a family of maps #{g : \Pi_{(a : A)}(D(f(a)) \to B(a))}.
}

\p{
Such a morphism induces a natural transformation of functors, but it is not provable
that such data is equivalent to the data of a natural transformation for polynomial
endofunctors on arbitrary types. In general, morphisms of polynomial endofunctors are
better behaved.
}

\p{
Notice that morphisms of polynomial endofunctors are \em{not} the same as morphisms
of their underlying [type families](Foundation.TypeFamilies), even though a
polynomial endofunctor is defined to be just a type family. This is because, in the
action of a polynomial endofunctor, the positions appear in a negative position of
the type signature. Therefore, the map on positions (above #{g}) goes the opposite
direction compared to a morphism of type families.
}

\p{
Beware also that some authors take morphisms of polynomial endofunctors to mean
\em{cartesian morphisms}, which are morphisms whose family of maps on positions is a
family of equivalences. We do not use this convention, and reserve the term
\em{cartesian morphism} for such morphisms.
}

\agda{
module _
  {𝓤1 𝓤2 𝓥1 𝓥2 : Level}
  (P@(A ◃ B) : 𝑃 𝓤1 𝓤2)
  (Q@(C ◃ D) : 𝑃 𝓥1 𝓥2)
  where

  record Hom𝑃 : Type (𝓤1 ⊔ 𝓤2 ⊔ 𝓥1 ⊔ 𝓥2) where
    constructor mk-Hom𝑃
    field
      shp : A → C
      pos : (a : A) → D (shp a) → B a

  open Hom𝑃
}
}

\subtree[stt-00SX]{
\taxon{Definition}
\title{Composition of morphisms of polynomial endofunctors}
\author{fredrikbakke}

\agda{
id-Hom𝑃
  : {𝓤1 𝓤2 : Level} (P : 𝑃 𝓤1 𝓤2) → Hom𝑃 P P
id-Hom𝑃 P = mk-Hom𝑃 id (λ a → id)

infixr 40 _∘Hom𝑃_

_∘Hom𝑃_
  : {𝓤1 𝓤2 𝓥1 𝓥2 𝓦1 𝓦2 : Level}
  → {P : 𝑃 𝓤1 𝓤2} {Q : 𝑃 𝓥1 𝓥2} {R : 𝑃 𝓦1 𝓦2}
  → Hom𝑃 Q R → Hom𝑃 P Q → Hom𝑃 P R
G ∘Hom𝑃 F
  = mk-Hom𝑃
      ( G .Hom𝑃.shp ∘ F .Hom𝑃.shp)
      ( λ a → F .Hom𝑃.pos a ∘ G .Hom𝑃.pos (F .Hom𝑃.shp a))

concat-Hom𝑃
  : {𝓤1 𝓤2 𝓥1 𝓥2 𝓦1 𝓦2 : Level}
  → {P : 𝑃 𝓤1 𝓤2} {Q : 𝑃 𝓥1 𝓥2} {R : 𝑃 𝓦1 𝓦2}
  → Hom𝑃 P Q → Hom𝑃 Q R → Hom𝑃 P R
concat-Hom𝑃 F G = G ∘Hom𝑃 F
}
}
